segments.text: Testing one, two, three.
Testing one, two, three.
All right.
Dr. Gage, would you please tell us a little about yourself, your early origins, and how you came to be a Texas Aggie?
Well, I was born and reared in the hill country in a small town called San Saba.
And no one from either side of my family had ever gone to college.
When I was in junior high, I was on a 4-H judging team.
And we came to 4-H Roundup and the state contest here.
And that was my first exposure ever to a college or university campus.
But it planted a seed very clearly in my mind.
And I was always very inquisitive.
had as a child gone out to a shed behind the house and played the mad scientist and had dreams of discovering something through research and experimentation.
You had a chemistry set.
I had a chemistry set and made my own chemistry set by
Oh, different concoctions that I would mix up and try to poison red ants, quite honestly.
Well, if you had found that, you really would have been a major inventor.
I might have had a patent and been able to retire.
And from then on, being reared on a small farm and ranch, had a very close tie to animals and to veterinary medicine.
And decided that, and then through high school, that I wanted to study veterinary medicine.
But I had always, since junior high, been in leadership positions.
And through high school, and even held some state offices.
So there was, from the very beginning, a real interest in my life always to take a leadership role.
But I knew that college education was absolutely essential.

And I worked my way through college with the help of my parents, starting first at Tarleton for one year, mainly due to the fact that I got a couple of scholarships that made a big impact and difference.
And we were from a very poor family.
And then the next year, I transferred to A&M.
knowing that it was the only veterinary college and clearly where I wanted to go from the beginning and would have come here as a freshman had I been able to have additional scholarship help.
I was one of the fortunate people who got into veterinary college in two years.
Where?
What year was that?
That was in 1962 was my first year on this campus.
which would have been then my second year of pre-veterinary medical work.
Then I entered veterinary college in the fall of 1963.
We were in, or the veterinary college was on a three-year, year-round curriculum.
So I could get a doctor of veterinary medicine degree in three years, but it meant going the total summer because it was really three semesters compacted into a total year schedule.
And I recall that we had a couple of semesters in which we had 39 contact hours in class and laboratory per week.
So it was rigorous.
That's tough.
But as I look back,
I'm grateful for that opportunity because I was able to get an undergraduate and a doctor's degree in a total of only five years.
Very good.
And it added at least two years to my productive career.
So I graduated in 1966 with my doctor of veterinary medicine degree and that was in August because we were on that kind of a time schedule.
And ten days later, I started a post-doctoral residency and graduate program in neurosurgery at Auburn University.
Okay.
And found myself also teaching veterinary students who were older than I because they had, in most cases, a four-year undergraduate, and then they were in their fourth year of veterinary college.
How did you get into neurosurgery?
That was brand new.

It was brand new and was fortuitous for me because it was at the same time that a lot of the sophistication of human medicine was being applied to veterinary medicine and the public was willing and able to pay for it.
And Auburn had a great reputation for their neurosurgery and had the premier small animal neurosurgeon in the nation.
Did anyone here encourage you in that direction?
I had encouragement from two surgeons here.
And I had an opportunity to either go to Auburn or to Colorado State.
And I had really become excited during veterinary college about surgery because it was kind of a challenge.
There are no two cases alike.
There's a lot of excitement in it.
And I found that I also had good surgical skills.

And when the opportunity then at Auburn presented itself, I left in 1966 and completed a master's in residency and became board certified as a diplomate of the American College of Veterinary Surgeons in neurosurgery.
I taught...
Which was probably a rare...
Rare Beast at the time.
It was and taught one quarter.

They were on a quarter system at Auburn and then in March of 1969 I was given an opportunity to come back to Texas A&M as assistant professor and at the time they had no neurosurgeon and it was almost like handing me an opportunity on a platter
to develop a complete specialty in that discipline.
Now they had a neurologist and I had done a great deal of work also in neurophysiology.
Who was the neurologist?
Dr. Charles Hall, who is still on faculty.
So he and I really formed a team and he handled the neurology cases and I did all the neurosurgery.
And I was here from 74 to 82 and was promoted to associate professor after only, I think, two years as assistant professor here.
And during my tenure here in that position,
I had the opportunity to really travel the world in presenting seminars and continuing education programs on the new techniques in surgery.
I had the opportunity to do a lot of the pioneering work in neurosurgery.
Who sponsored that?
Was that through the U.S. government programs?
No, a lot of it.
would be through the professional associations.
And the American Veterinary Medical Association, the American Animal Hospital Association, and then many other professional groups throughout the country.
And the opportunities to present some of the new surgical techniques that we were performing in the dog
Before I quit surgery and entered administration, I did over 1,500 spinal procedures, predominantly for slipped discs and broken backs, spinal fractures, in which the animal would be paraplegic.
And unlike the human, where they're often placed in a wheelchair,
that's not a viable option for an animal.
I had a friend who had a dog like that.
Well, if we could do them early, yeah.
I got many of them to walk again, and that was so gratifying.
I did a great deal of brain surgery in the dog for tumors, for fractures, and also birth.
problem, congenital problem, called hydrocephalus, which is water on the brain.
And I would use the same... Can you detect that at birth?
Can you?

And I would use the same system that's used in the human infant, which is to insert a tube into the chamber of the brain that collected the excess fluid, and it drains with a one-way pump down into the heart.
And that was exciting to see the results.
And then in 1974
I was given an opportunity at a young age of only 32 to become professor and head of the Department of Urban Practice in the new College of Veterinary Medicine at the University of Tennessee.
And I will never forget, I got a call from
a man named W.W. Armstead who had at one time been dean of vet med here.

He had gone to Michigan State and he had called me at Michigan State and I was in surgery lab and they called me out of lab and I went down to my office and took the call and he said, I don't know whether you've heard but I'm going to become the dean of a new college of veterinary medicine that we're going to start at the University of Tennessee.
And I'd like to know if you'd have interest in becoming head of the Department of Small Animal Medicine and Surgery, which we're going to call urban practice.
Well, you know, at my young age, I thought I'd be delighted to talk to you about it because I still had that interest in academic administration.
And even when I went through veterinary college,
I looked up to Al Price who was the dean at the time and thought one day I'd like to do that.
And my wife and I visited with him in Denver, Colorado at the American Veterinary Medical Association and then we flew up in August of that year and interviewed at UT Knoxville and during the

time before we went I kept thinking well I wonder how many people are going to interview and you know they're probably going to look at full professors and people who have been out there a long time and lo and behold during the interview I was offered the job.
Yeah I haven't, I don't know Armistead I don't believe but I have heard a lot about him and I have a feeling that's the way he works.
He's a fantastic administrator.
He knew what he was going to do before he did it.
And he offered us the job on the spot.
And I thought, well, we're not going to accept or he'll think I'm too eager.
And we'll get home and think about it.
You were really being nervy.
So about two days later, I called him back.
And we accepted.
And I was the first person to join him after he went there as dean.
And we went in November the 1st of 1974.
And we were there eight years and built the complete program.
I was responsible for that academic program and department.
And then I was responsible for construction of all the facilities, which in today's funding level would be probably close to a $50 million project.
Who was president of Tennessee at that time?
It doesn't matter.
Jack Williams had been there.
Yeah, he was not there.
Ed Bowling was president of the system.
I can't recall.
He was a historian, though.
Yeah, that's what I was thinking, too.
I guess vaguely in my mind, but I can't remember who it was.
It seemed like his first name was Jack.
I can't recall what his first name was.
But it was a tremendous administrative experience for me.
Were you back in surgery, too, at the same time?
No, I pretty well gave up surgery to devote almost full time then to administration and to start a new program from ground zero and to hire every faculty member.
I would say you did the hiring.
That's exciting.
To devise a brand new curriculum from scratch
It was, for my age, just a unique experience.
And to work with the state legislature, with the system, the university system, to work within the largest university of 30,000 student enrollment there, and to have that kind of a
opportunity is really an administrative experience that few people ever have.
Sure, that's right.
And I have the greatest admiration for Armistead.
He was a true statesman and one of the most astute administrators I have ever worked with and efficient.
And then in 1982, I was contacted about the associate dean for academic and clinical programs here.
And after eight years, I thrive on challenges, and I needed a new challenge.
It was ready, and it was an advancement.
So I took the position here.
Was he coming back home, too?
Did that have anything to do with it?
Absolutely.
My own alma mater and home.
And who was Dean?
George Shelton.
Shelton, okay.
Had you known him before?
Not really.
I had only known him by meeting at professional meetings on a national basis.
And I had served as a consultant though here to the professional curricula revision because we had put a new curriculum in place which a lot of people were looking at at the time.
So I did have an opportunity to come back periodically, and I think that that is one reason that they were looking at me very specifically.
So what they did, they really combined two responsibilities.
I had oversight for the veterinary teaching hospital as well as all of the academic and student programs in the college.
In fact, now they have three associate deans.
That's what happens, doesn't it?
For the one position I had.
Always happens that way.
And I had great opportunities under George because he was such a delegating individual, and I had...
a lot of wonderful growing opportunities in that role.
I liked him.
I got to know him somehow or other along the way.
He was a true gentleman.
In fact, I told him once he was too nice to be a dean.
That's right.
Probably so.
And in that role, I really had some opportunities to serve on a large number of university-wide committees.
And it gave me, I think, a growing opportunity for growth
in my own capabilities and the contacts and the kinds of responsibilities on a university-wide basis.
Yeah, because really at that time, I think the College of Veterinary Medicine was sort of isolated from the main university.
It was, very much.
And people on the campus really didn't think much about your participation.
And I think that we really made strides to bring the college back into the mainstream, and particularly with the growth of the undergraduate program in the college.
And then in 1989, I had conversation with Bill Mobley about a position in the president's office as chief of staff and executive assistant to the president.
And after having served from 82 to 89, again, I was really looking toward upper administration, which was truly
my long-term goal.
Were you out of the classroom?
Yes, totally.
I would do guest lecturing and did some lectures on professional ethics, on stress and time management for the professional.
And I would, on a few occasions, give some neurosurgery
lectures on one or two subjects but very, very little.
And so in 89 I moved to the president's office and of course that was a tremendous time of growth and expansion of my administrative horizons.
I was in charge also of all state affairs and the legislative process.
Now, I had done that in the veterinary college for each biennium because we had a separate line item budget.
In fact, I had been a part of moving the veterinary college from formula to line item funding.
So I had already worked through and knew what the legislative process was and the legislative appropriations process.
So then I was in charge of it for the whole university when I became chief of staff.
This was primarily your assignment with Dr. Mobley was to be the liaison and the anti-man in Austin.
And to serve as the state affairs, and also to serve liaison to many of the external constituent groups, the former students, the Mothers Club, and many others.
But he also gave me a large number of internal assignments, some of which were partly in the academic side.
I had responsibility for the task force that made the recommendations in the international program office and the changes that we implemented there.
And there were others like that.
And that was for the full calendar year of 89 to 90.
And then in January of 90, I was named interim provost and vice president.
And then in July of that same year, I was named vice president for academic affairs and provost.
And then the title was changed a year later to senior vice president and provost.

Of course, that entailed a second administrative officer in the university and the chief academic officer with all of the academic programs, all ten colleges, the two library directors, all of the academic support areas, the research agenda, admissions and records all the way to placement.
So these people reported to you first usually rather than straight to you?
All of those reported to me before coming to the press.
And then, of course, serving in that role, I served as acting president in his absence.
And it was...

great training for where I sit today because really there were no major surprises in coming to this office because I had spent a whole year in the president's office and then in that role so many of the agenda items were common and we always had a very close relationship and the president's executive staff discussed most all the issues that were before us.
Did he have any unique administrative styles that

be singular or anything I know I know he was really conscious of the technique and style of management that's obviously yeah yeah he uh his bag he uh is a very efficient administrator and uh a very open and good communicator with clear uh delegation and I had always told him in both of the tubes

positions that I held with him that when I was given a responsibility I was just going to do the best that I could and what I thought was to be done and if there was something in it that I wasn't doing right or he wanted change let me know that I wasn't going to bother him and and that's the kind of freedom that we had and I think the freedom that we had also was built upon uh

almost identical kinds of work styles because he and I are very close in work style, in delegation, and giving a person responsibility and holding them accountable and matching the authority with the responsibility.
At this point, did you pretty well pull out of the Austin scene?
Yes.
Once I moved to the provost position,

office i really pulled out of being the lead person in austin but in my role as senior vice president provost i still had a big involvement particularly in compiling the legislative appropriation request our office did that because most of the budget is from the academic side
So in one sense, I didn't pull out, and I still had to testify in the hearings, but I wasn't having to be in Austin, walk in the halls of Austin.
And that was then transferred to a person that he brought in after me, and that's Ellen Perrone, who was handling all of our state and federal affairs.
Since, well, 89, 90 and so forth, when you moved into the...
basically university administration.
Have the problems, have the issues, have the concerns changed in that relatively short period?
Or do you say, essentially, are we dealing with the same situations and problems you dealt with when you walked in the door in any lab or something?
No, I think we're dealing with a number of changing issues.
One has been the continued resource and funding constraints and very difficult economic situations.
Right.
Do you see that improving?
I see it on the horizon of improving, hopefully within the next biennium or the one following it.
Yeah, that's sort of what Dr.
Mogul projected.
I think that there are some positive indicators
not only about the overall economy, but I think the realization that unless we make the investment in public and higher ed, that our future is limited as a competitive economy and society.
And more and more do I see appreciation and a grasp of that importance by the state leadership and the general public of the state.
It has not come easily.
but it has come through our own efforts of educating the public as to that importance.
Another issue is before us that will continue to be before us, and that is the demographic changes, the ethnic population changes of this state.
It's a sensitive issue.
It's one of considerable debate, has been, will continue to be,
But it's one that we have got to recognize as a part of the demographic changes of this state.
The state legislature has already begun in its makeup to be very reflective of the changing population.
And if you look at the projections for the future, very clearly there will be no ethnic majority in the state.
And we have as a state institution a great responsibility to educate all of the workforce of the population of the state for the future.
If we don't, then we will continue to see the welfare roles increasing and the drain on the economy and continued needs for additional criminal justice increases in the prison system.
And education is the basic deterrent and antidote to those.
And we've just absolutely got to intervene and keep
all of the ethnic groups of the population in the educational pipeline so that we do educate the workforce of tomorrow.
Now when you say the educational pipeline, you're talking about the A&M educational pipeline.
I'm talking about even public schools.
We've got close ties now and intervention programs with the public schools.

to try to keep these kids from dropping out in the seventh, eighth, ninth, tenth grade so that they at least graduate through high school, and then we hopefully will have them in junior college and universities then later.
Do you think A&M has some sort of an advantage or disadvantage in...
diversifying or making this kind of...
I think we have a disadvantage for one reason as far as the enrollment numbers on this campus and that is that we do not have
our location in a major metropolitan area.
Where there is that diversity.
Where there is that diversity and where there is already that pool of minorities living at home and who can attend.
We have to recruit them to this location and for some

groups it's even more difficult because it is a fairly long distance from home so that works to our disadvantage and we don't have the numbers within the community to build even a professional network and that impacts our ability to recruit faculty and staff and I do think that it
causes us to have to work doubly hard.
But we're making great gains.
And we have the largest minority enrollment this year that we've ever had.
We have a very substantial increase in Hispanic members.
And we've made great gains in faculty again this year.
And I am convinced that we have now begun to get
that base overhead number that's needed.
To build a pool to work from.
To build a pool and to build a network that will help us in the future.
But I think that's going to continue to be a big issue for this university and all of them, the universities in the state.
I think funding is going to continue to be one.
I think that the other whole area
is that we've got to work on is the public relations area.
There have been a number of adverse national media accounts of some improprieties at other institutions and research funding.
of scientific misconduct, of perhaps not the right communication of faculty workloads, so that it's created the wrong impression.
Has any of this been directed at A&M specifically?
No, not at all.
And that's where we're fortunate.
We are.
We have not had any of that directed at us.
Stanford was the first with their problems in indirect cost.
Harvard got into some difficulties in the scientific misconduct area and some publicity.
And those... That's good that you're conscious of that because I think that's been something we've not been very conscious of.
We've been very fortunate here.
I think that...
There is no doubt that our current endowment campaign and the continued efforts in looking toward external funding from the private sector is one of our most important priorities for the future.
I think that we will no longer see the kind of state support that we had enjoyed prior to, say, 1985.
And it behooves us to make sure that we continue to build public support.
Well, that's one area we certainly have a leg up on.
And we haven't, as all of higher ed,
been very effective in communicating our value and our worth.
Probably not, that's right.

And we've had some lack of communication of what the faculty workload is and a lot of misperception that faculty only teach, you know, three hours and they're through rather than the number of sections, the number of contact hours, the number of hours in preparation.
and the number of hours in grading papers and student counseling.
We've not done a good job of communicating that.
Do you think it's going to be more and more conflict over that kind of issue, which also involves the research?
Absolutely.
Absolutely.
And do you see us moving more and more heavily into a research orientation and to a graduate level?
Slowly, because we're a major research university and now being the eighth largest university and with...
a very large graduate program, and with the commitment that we have made in Target 2000 to move toward 25% graduate professional enrollment, we will continue to slowly move in that direction.
But at the same time, balancing what I do believe is our mandated

responsibility as a land grant institution to maintain a very strong and large undergraduate program that infuses the cutting edge technology and the research that's being done into the classroom and continuing to not only take the top kids from the state, but at the same time in the land grant mission,
taking still some broad spectrum of students from across the state.
That's good.
That's a good point.
And that's key to us.
I think in our striving for excellence sometimes we ignore the realities of the world.
And I think that we've really done that recently with the new initiatives that fortunately I had the opportunity of leading in the undergraduate education programs.
where we re-emphasized teaching.
We revamped the Center for Teaching Excellence.

We put the Center for Academic Enhancement in place, which is somewhat the other spectrum of the honors program in our National Merit Scholars to help the kids who are having trouble making the transition.
So we're trying to look at both sides and both spectrums of the student capabilities.
and about 15 new initiatives that we actually put in place to enhance undergraduate.
That's actually been the great strength of A&M through the years.
They've brought people in who had no other opportunities, and A&M gave them that opportunity.
And I think the other thing that's helped us really be a leader in this area
has been that commitment and that tradition historically.

And the traditions of this campus, the support of the former students, and then the some 700 student organizations on campus that provide leadership and individual development opportunities because it creates a family atmosphere.
That's a remarkable environment.
I don't think any other campus has anything like that.
And I'll tell you something that people fail to realize.
We mentioned a moment ago that being in a small community probably worked against us on having a higher number of minorities.
But at the same time, it works for us on the retention and...
building the loyalty to the school because we're not in a major metropolitan area and we become the focus and we become a family.
And when you capture that and combine it with the traditions,
It is what really, I think, protects and promotes and enhances the Aggie spirit.
Well, what's remarkable to me is that they've been able to preserve that aura in spite of the tremendous growth.
Colas and Wires, in my mind, are two of the great inspirations for keeping that going.
You know, the Corps of Cadets still being prominent and now growing again.
We protect and preserve the traditions and the history of this university through those very clearly.
The theme of this revision basically, of course, is change.
And I noticed one of the things you mentioned when you stepped into this office was that you were interested in changing or adapting our students to the new global
environment, so how do you see A&M's mission in the global economy?

I think that we've really got some exciting programs and if you look at the number of our students involved in international study abroad experiences and student exchanges and the number of courses that we have on campus,
We lead the state, and our goal and priority has been to infuse the international dimension into all of our academic and student programs.
And that's done through new courses that have been developed.
It's done through study abroad experiences.
It's done through our campuses in Japan and Italy and now Mexico City.
It's also done... What's going to happen there, incidentally?
In Mexico City?
Yeah.
It will provide us an opportunity to continue to build partnerships and programmatic development opportunities with institutions in Mexico.
A year-round office or a year-round academic program?
It's a full year-round office, but we will not teach the courses out of that office.
Except for executive development, business development kinds of courses.
But it serves really as an office to bring partnerships together and agreements.
We now have some 500 research programs around the world.
We have 100 memorandum agreements.
with other institutions across the whole world.
And it's just a constant travel now back and forth of our faculty and foreign visitors to this campus.
And with those interactions, our students are clearly brought into contact with the kinds of international dimension and the globalization that's occurring on almost a daily basis.
It really is.
And then with 2,800 foreign students on this campus, international students, they rub elbows with them every day.
That makes a difference.
Absolutely.
In the environment and opportunities of the Aggies.
And the recruiters are here on campus telling us that we must prepare our graduates to be able to function competitively.
in the new global village.
So therefore, that is a reason that we're in Jesus.
I sense that my students in class are actually becoming a little more conscious of the world than they were not too long ago.
It really is.
Very clearly.
Let me ask two more questions, I guess.
I don't want to take up all your lunch date, I know.
What is the enlarging Texas A&M University system?
Is it a blessing or a burden?
And then I guess finally would be your advices for whoever is in the president's chair.
What needs to be done for the future?
Well, I'm strongly supportive of the expansion that has occurred in the Texas A&M University system very clearly.

this will be the flagship university within the system and should be and there needs to be a very clear understanding that it will serve in that priority role but in that role there is an enormous expectation that it serves as a leadership role and its leadership role should be to help

collaboratively and in partnership with the other institutions in all of the academic research and extension programs and I think that it will serve as an opportunity for us to work in not only research but also in some of the academic programs with their needs of development

and the needs of development, particularly in South Texas, and the expertise and consultation that we can give, I think that we can benefit by the fact that we should be able to recruit into our graduate programs students from their institution, and in turn perhaps even educate and prepare some of the faculty of the future.
And that's what the system has always served, like yourself and Earl Rudder and so many others.
No question.
What was the second part about it?
Well, it was a totally different question, I guess, and that is what advices would you give to a president of Texas A&M University?
My advice to anyone who serves...
in this role is to, first of all, be a good communicator.
Now, the person has got to have the kinds of experience and track record in handling a very large, complex organization
And the person has got to surround him or herself with the most competent people that they possibly can.
It is too big for any one person.
They must develop the team approach of people who are capable of handling the areas of assigned responsibility.
The person has got to have a tremendous organizational and time management ability.
and has got to have a tremendous amount of energy.
Because some of these days are 15, 16 hour days.
They've got to have a vision to see the big picture.
They've got to know what academic and student and athletic programs mean to a university.
They've also got to be very astute to the politics that are involved in dealing with
many different external constituencies will have to be astute to the state legislature and elected officials and to build a trust and communication with these constituencies.
No question.
No question.
And has
I think got to make sure that they stay closely in communications with the faculty, the staff, and the students internally.
Cannot become detached.
Must know what's going on even though areas will be delegated.
And I think has got to recognize that there are issues which have to be faced.
And I've made this statement before that the easiest way to mishandle an issue is to ignore it.
You have to hit them head on and try to come to a definitive resolution to each and every one of them.
will have to develop a fairly thick skin.
Yeah, I bet.
Because you're going to get a lot of advice from many people.
Inside and out.
Inside and out.
And to not only be a good communicator in the public forum or in the oral forum, but also in writing.
Yeah.
Because the letters and memoranda and other op-eds and pieces of information that go out, people are going to analyze and evaluate every word.
Yeah, they do.
You don't think about that.
To see what the meaning might be behind it.
That's right.
And that gets into, I guess, the political sensitivity and astuteness of what is and is not said.
That's part of it.
You have to stop and think about everything you write.
That's right.
But it's an exciting opportunity.
I love administration.
It's a challenge and I like to take on the competition and play to win.
And I get charged up in speaking before alumni groups or former students and to many of different public forums.
Well, you've got an appreciative audience.
They're really a good audience.
And it really is exciting to do that.
I would think this would be about as good a time to be a president of Texas A&M as any time we've had in the past.
I really believe that because...
It's fortunate that the direction, I think, is well set.
Yes.
And I don't think that it's a time in which the university was faced with major problems of needing to change directions, that we're on the upward movement.
I sense that, too.
In interviewing Vandenberg, yourself, Richardson, Mobley, and everyone I've talked to, there's a consensus there.
And that's where I'm fortunate, because I've been a part of building...
the plan of where we are and where we're going.
Yeah, that's great.
I better let you go, I guess.
You've got another point.
Well, I've enjoyed it.
Well, I really appreciate it.
Well, you're more than welcome.
More than welcome.
